        "text": "The document discusses potential revenue streams for battery energy storage systems using a profit maximization model under two scenarios. The first scenario involves energy price arbitrage, where energy is purchased when prices are low and sold when prices are high. The second scenario involves co-optimizing energy and ancillary services in the day-ahead market. Both scenarios use a year's worth of pricing data across 350 pricing nodes, with a 24-hour optimization horizon. Battery characteristics and constraints are detailed in Table 1.7.\n\nCharging and discharging costs are calculated using default energy bids from the Energy Storage and Distributed Energy Resources (ESDER) initiative. Market revenues in the first scenario are based on day-ahead market prices, while the second scenario also uses ancillary services marginal prices.\n\nThe document also includes an analysis of a hypothetical combined cycle unit, modeled as a multi-stage generating resource. The optimization model ensures only one configuration is committed based on profitability. Table 1.3 outlines key assumptions, and Table 1.4 presents results for three price scenarios for a unit in Northern California.",
